Certainly! Below is a TikZ LaTeX code that creates a top-down view of a head with three distinct coronal levels, each represented by a different shape and color. Additionally, it includes an X-ray beam coming from an X-ray tube and a resulting shadow on an X-ray film.

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]

% Draw the head outline
\draw[thick, black] (0,0) circle (2);

% Draw the three coronal levels
\fill[topaz] (0,0) ellipse (1.8 and 0.6);
\fill[dandelion] (0,0) rectangle (-1.4,-0.5);
\fill[burnt orange] (0,0) rectangle (1.4,-0.5);

% Label the coronal levels
\node at (0,0.7) {Cranium};
\node at (0,-0.9) {Skull Base};
\node at (0,-1.5) {Brain};

% Draw the X-ray tube
\draw[->, thick, blue] (-2,2) -- (2,2);

% Draw the X-ray film
\node at (2,2) [rectangle, minimum width=4cm, minimum height=2cm, draw, fill=white, inner sep=2pt] {};
\node at (2,1.5) {X-ray Film};

% Draw the shadow on the X-ray film
\draw[thick, gray] (2,1) rectangle (2.5,1.2);
\draw[thick, gray] (2,1) rectangle (1.5,1.2);

\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

### Explanation:
- **Head Outline**: A simple circle represents the head.
- **Coronal Levels**:
  - **Cranium**: Represented as an ellipse above the head.
  - **Skull Base**: Represented as a rectangle below the head but above the brain.
  - **Brain**: Represented as a rectangle below the skull base.
- **X-ray Tube**: An arrow pointing from the left to the right representing the X-ray beam.
- **X-ray Film**: A white rectangle to the right of the head where the shadow will be cast.

